y, defense of which had previously limited governments to unenforceable statements of opprobrium against violator nations, has changed over the past two decades to allow for more aggressive action in support of international moral standards. As a result, human rights have gained increasing importance in the arena of world politics.While researching this book in Guatemala and El Salvador, Burgerman interviewed government officials, negotiators, analysts, and human rights workers, and accompanied UN observer teams in their travels through rainforests and mountainous terrain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aHuman rights workersxPolitical activity. 0aHuman rightsxInternational cooperation. 0aHuman rightsxPolitical aspects. 0aHuman rightszEl Salvador. 0aHuman rightszGuatemala. 0aPressure groups. 4aHumanities & Human Rights. 4aLatin American & Caribbean Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172240040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501722400423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501722400/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles